<TITLE> Appeals hearing in Mujib murder case ends for the day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 8 (bdnews24.com)  The Supreme Court ended arguments hearing from the prosecution side in the Bangabandhu murder appeals for the day on Sunday. The five-member Appellate Division bench, headed by justice Mohammed Tafazzal Islam, began the 25th day's hearing at around 9:45am with attorney general Mahbubey Alam presenting his arguments. Hearing for the day ended at around 1:30pm. Before Alam, the chief state counsel in the case, Anisul Haque, delivered his arguments. The prosecution started its arguments on Nov 2. On Oct 5, the newly formed bench began hearing the appeals against previous court sentences to hang some convicts in the case for assassinating the nation's founding leader 'Bangabandhu' Sheikh Mujibur Rahman on Aug 15, 1975. The case was filed in 1996 with Dhanmondi Police Station against 24 persons during the Awami League government by revoking the indemnity ordinance. The trial court awarded death sentences to 15 of the 20 accused. The High Court later gave a split verdict in the caseJustice Md Ruhul Amin upheld death sentences of 10 of the convicts but Justice A B M Khairul Haque retained death sentences of all the 15. Justice Mohammad Fazlul Karim of a third High Court bench upheld death sentences of 12 and acquitted three. Of the 12 death convicts, five appealed against their sentence in the Appellate Division. 
